2star  aIn his introduction to this collection of essays by constitutional experts, Philip Bryden says that Canadians can be proud of their commitment to the protection of rights and liberties in the Charter. Canada, he believes, is a better place to live then it would be otherwise. Nevertheless, as the essays in this book reveal, the case in favour of the Charter is not simple or one-sided. For instance, Kim Campbell, minister of justice at the time of writing, and Jeffrey Simpson of the Globe and Mail express concern that the Charter promotes a rights discourse that threatens to overwhelm the ordinary politics of recognizing and accommodating different interests. Dean Lynn Smith of the University of British Columbia law faculty observes that the Charter rights are better understood as complementing than as supplanting traditional mechanisms. The authors, diverse in background and outlook, reflect varying points of view but share a significant degree of consensus on issues that need to be addressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil rightszCanada. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aBryden, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryden, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCampbell, Rt. Hon. Kim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aElliot, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedenberg, Edgar Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Lysiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLajoie, Andrte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichelman, Frank I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab